│ THOUGHT: The miscompilation arises because InstCombine uses the nsz flag on the fcmp to treat +0.0 and -0.0 as  │
│ equal and rewrites `fcmp olt x, +0.0` to `fcmp ole x, -0.0`. However, the select returns a specific signed zero │
│ (-0.0), and the nsz flag only applies to the comparison, not to the select result. As shown, for x = +0.0, the  │
│ original yields +0.0, but the transformed yields -0.0, which is incorrect. The fix is to prevent zero-sign      │
│ changing rewrites of the comparison when the select result is sensitive to the sign of zero (i.e., one of the   │
│ select operands is a signed zero literal). I will inspect the InstCombine code to identify the transformation   │
│ and then adjust it to avoid altering the zero sign in such contexts.                                            │
│                                                                                                                 │
│ ```bash                                                                                                         │
│ grep -Rn --exclude-dir=build --exclude-dir=.git -E 'fcmp.*nsz|nsz|-0\.0|NegativeZero|isNegativeZero|signbit'    │
│ llvm/lib | sed -n '1,200p'                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                             │
