│ THOUGHT: The miscompilation arises because simplifyFCmpInst is performing predicate-changing folds when         │
│ comparing against zero under the nsz flag, which then results in a select producing -0.0 for input +0.0. To     │
│ conservatively prevent this, I will add a targeted guard in InstructionSimplify: for FP compares with RHS or    │
│ LHS equal to any zero and with nsz set, bail out early (return nullptr). This avoids altering predicates around │
│ zero under nsz and prevents exposing a specific signed zero downstream.                                         │
│                                                                                                                 │
│ ```bash                                                                                                         │
│ sed -i '4078a \  // Under NSZ, avoid simplifying FP compares against zero to prevent predicate changes\\\n  //  │
│ that may expose a specific signed-zero in downstream selects.\n  if (FMF.noSignedZeros()) {\n    const APFloat  │
│ *ZeroC = nullptr;\n    if ((match(RHS, m_AnyZeroFP()) || match(LHS, m_AnyZeroFP())))\n      return nullptr;\n   │
│ }' llvm/lib/Analysis/InstructionSimplify.cpp && submit-patch                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                             │
